@{u}6.2.1. Changes in the main window@{uu}

In the main window you will only find two new buttons: "Reset IDs" and "Reset Names". The first one resets to standard setting assigned display IDs that are also used by Intuition to indicate a screen mode.

This becomes necessary if you are working with a mulfunctioning DisplayID database and you want to reset on a certain point.

"Reset Names" resets names associated with DisplayIDs to default names: "color depth Height x Width" (For example "8bit 800x600"). As you can associate, thanks to ModeMaster and ProBench3, a particualr name to any single DisplayID, we implemented this function to help you going back do default settings.

To use ProBench in 16 bit modes do the same as you are used to do for 8 bit modes. Chose the desired mode and click on the DisplayID column. List content should change to a number in the range over 0x4000900. Now save settings so that this mode will be available after the first reset either for Intuition (ScreenMode-requester) as well as for CyberGraphX.
@endnode

@node "2.2 Changes in the Frequency editor" "2.2 Changes in the Frequency editor"
@font topaz 8
@wordwrap
@prev "2.1 Changes in the main window"
@toc "ProBench3"

@{u}6.2.2. Changes in the Frequency Editor@{uu}

Now you have to find a string gadget to enter resolution's name. This gadget may contain up to 32 characters and should be used to identify a resolution more quickly. So the mode "320*256" may become like "VGA, 640*512 HIRES INTERLACE", and so forth.
@endnode

@node "2.3 Changes in the Globals window" "2.3 Changes in the Globals window"
@font topaz 8
@wordwrap
@prev "2.2 Changes in the Frequency editor"
@toc "ProBench3"

@{u}6.2.3. Changes in the Globals window@{uu}

The Globals window is working now as a control panel for several new ProBench3 options. These are, in details:

@{b}VMemBitMap@{ub}

It is allowed to manage hidden window areas in video RAM. This is a determining factor for opening an moving window speed. If this option is not enabled, the memory manging in the board is limited to screens. This option should be then disabled if a fast screen switch priority is higher.

@{b}VMemBobs@{ub}

Blitter objects like icons, or drag'n'drop objects can be kept in the board for a more quick movement. If for generation of a such (little) object video RAM must be flushed, this can lead, on one hand, to a slow down in moving bobs and, in second place to an unusefull flush of other graphic objects (windows or whole screens).

@{b}Deep Find Color@{ub}

Changing a screen's color depth from 16 to 8 bit through HRControl and with this option disabled, a fast and simple color conversion algorithm is used, otherwise a slow one, which gives better results, is used. This option doesn't work when a "normal" change is performed by ScreenMode requester.

@{b}Sprite Colors@{ub}

Mouse pointer colors are always resetted together with the screen colors or when its shape is redefined.

@{b}Disable Blitter@{ub}

It disables the Merlin blitter. This option is meant to limit error causes only. Usually you should keep blitter enabled!

@{b}Fix ShapeShifter-Screen@{ub}

This is an extra option for C. Bauer's outstanding Mac emulator. When this option is enabled, Mac screen is kept on the Board. By this can you avoid that the Mac-sign draws on another screen. For this option you must chose CyberGraphX as video driver. If you use XCalibur digitizer you cannot use any "fixed" ShapeShifer screens.

@{b}Optimize Layers@{ub}

This option leads to a faster window moving.

@{b}Force MerlinBitMaps@{ub}

When enabled, Merlin chunky bitmaps are used instead of Amiga planar ones. Merlin bitmaps are faster when using Merlin blitter, while Amiga bitmaps are faster when using Amiga blitter. Althoudh it is normally better to switch this option on, it may occasionally lead to wrong display, for instance in the color marker of colorwheel.gadget. Enable this if you want a fast and sometimes wrong display, disable this if you want an always correct but somewhat slower one.

@{b}Allocate BitMaps first in...@{ub}

Establish if and how memory managements work inside the board. For this three ways exist: (Merlin) video ram is used, and only when full it is flushed and Amiga memory is used. In the case not enough Amiga memory is available what may happen is unpredictable. (Merlin and Amiga) it is always possible to additionally allocate Amiga memory so that unpredictable results will not happen. Furthermore, flushing of graphics in video RAM is faster. This method, however, uses more Amiga memory than the first one does. (Amiga) Memory management can be completely disabled and only actual screen can be shown through the graphic memory. This is the slowest method and it still needs even more Amiga memory.

@{b}Max. BlitPlanes@{ub}

By this you establish when Blitter is detached from CPU for planar to chunky conversions. Although, under this circumstances, blitter speed can be higher it is more enjoyable to look at (i.e. flickering) to use blitter until a particular depth.

@{b}Optimize Spaces@{ub}

If, in a text, many white spaces appears, these can be drawn by a special routine. This can lead to a considerable speed increase when many spaces are in the output of programs, like in DirectoryOpus or text editors.

@{b}Copy areas min.@{ub}

Inicates the minimum space for Blitter enabling for copying areas. As preparing a copy operation whith blitter cannot happen at once, a fast CPU can be, up to a particular size, faster than Merlin Blitter.

@{b}Fill areas min.@{ub}

The same as Copy but referred to fill operation.

@{b}Line blit min.@{ub}

Here length/height of certain lines from which the blitter, by drawing, detaches from CPU are selected. Substantially same as for previous options applies. Also here a -1 exists to always draw with the CPU. Insert here a 0 to correct possible Merlin hardware troubles (wrong colors in vertical lines).
@endnode

@node "3. HRControl" "3. HRControl"
@font topaz 8
@wordwrap
@prev "2. ModeMaster"
